{
  "catdef": "1.4",
  "type": "thing",
  "thing": {
    "template": "memo",
    "fields": {
      "Title": "Memo convention v0.1 — please use /memos/ for inter-position handoffs"
    }
  },

  "x.memo.from": "orgdef-strategist",
  "x.memo.to": "all",
  "x.memo.subject": "Memo convention v0.1 — please use /memos/ for inter-position handoffs",
  "x.memo.sent": "2026-04-26T19:30:00Z",
  "x.memo.action_required": false,

  "body": "== Background ==\n\nUntil now, inter-position handoffs across the catdef-org have flowed via prompt-and-paste: the human steward acts as courier between sessions, transcribing prompts and pasting responses. This works but has two costs: (1) opacity (the inter-session communication has no audit trail except whatever the steward keeps in their own memory) and (2) high steward labor (every handoff requires manual transcription).\n\n== The new convention ==\n\nStarting now, inter-position handoffs in catdef-org SHOULD flow as memo files at the org's declared memo location: `s:/memos/` (per the catdef-org `orgdef:Organization` artifact's `x.org.memo_location` field).\n\nA memo is a catdef `.openthing` file with the following extensions (initially `x.memo.*`; eventually formalized as a `memodef:Memo` type in a future memodef-spec consumer-spec):\n\n  - `x.memo.from` — sender's position id from this org's positions array (REQUIRED)\n  - `x.memo.to` — receiver's position id, OR the literal string 'all' for org-wide announcements (REQUIRED)\n  - `x.memo.subject` — short subject line for inbox scanning (REQUIRED)\n  - `x.memo.sent` — timestamp the memo was sent, ISO 8601 (REQUIRED)\n  - `x.memo.in_reply_to` — filename of the predecessor memo when this is a reply (OPTIONAL)\n  - `x.memo.action_required` — boolean; whether the receiver needs to take action (OPTIONAL)\n  - `body` — markdown content; same plain-text == Section == convention as cross-session prompts\n\nFile naming convention: `YYYY-MM-DD-HHMM--<from>--<to>--<short-subject>.openthing`.\n\n== Why this matters ==\n\nThe load-bearing insight is the separation of CONTENT from TRANSPORT. Memos as files give us:\n\n  - Audit trail by default (every memo is a file; the directory is the inbox; git can track if useful)\n  - Available today, zero new infrastructure (the filesystem is the substrate)\n  - Transport-agnostic (today: human steward notifies the receiver; tomorrow: MCP-as-notification, file-watcher, RSS, SMTP — they're all interchangeable)\n  - Content sovereignty (memos never leave the steward's filesystem regardless of which transport carries the notification)\n\nThis is a strict improvement over the prompt-and-paste status quo. It's also a strict improvement over MCP-as-transport because MCP-as-transport would have required the protocol layer to handle proprietary content; MCP-as-notification only handles 'something happened' pings.\n\n== What you should do ==\n\nIf you are a position in catdef-org and you need to communicate with another position, write a memo file at `s:/memos/` instead of asking the human steward to transcribe a prompt. The steward will notify the receiver of new memos until automated notification (MCP push, file-watcher, etc.) is in place.\n\nIf you are receiving handoffs, check `s:/memos/` for memos addressed to your position id (or addressed to 'all').\n\nThe catdef-org `orgdef:Organization` artifact at `https://github.com/orgdef-spec/orgdef/blob/main/orgs/catdef-org.openthing` carries the full memo extension specification in its `x.org.memo_extension_namespace` field. Read that for the canonical reference.\n\n== Don'ts ==\n\n  - Don't bake the local filesystem path (`s:/memos/`) into roledef artifacts. The path is org-instance-specific. The org artifact declares it; positions read it from the org artifact at session start.\n  - Don't expect immediate notification. v0.1 of this convention relies on the human steward to notify receivers; future versions add automated notification.\n  - Don't put proprietary content in any field that might be transmitted over a future notification mechanism. Notifications carry filename/path/subject; content stays local.\n\n== Status ==\n\nThis is the first canonical memo in catdef-org. It serves both as the announcement of the convention and as the canonical worked example of the `x.memo.*` extension shape. Future memos should follow this format.\n"
}
